      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks. that's helpful. can u go a bit deeper into the mechanism? like why do neutrophils respond so much faster in an acute setting compared to lymphocytes? i'm trying to understand the actual cellular response/recruitment process.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Neutrophils are the body's rapid-response forces, allowing them to be quickly mobilized from the bone marrow and circulates to sites of acute bacterial infection through immediate chemotaxis. Lymphocytes, being central to adaptive immunity, require clonal expansion and differentiation to mount an effective response, which is a slower, more sustained process. This difference in the initiation time and recruitment speed dictates the immediate shift toward neutrophilia in acute emergencies.",
      "source": "target",
